label: Baptisms and Infant Deaths - 18th and 19th Centuries
description: Box 20 - Baptisms and Infant Deaths contains records created during the late-eighteenth and early-nineteenth centuries in Florida. Presumably, only individuals of predominantly white ancestry are recorded in the infant death entries Individuals referred to as moreno/a, cuarterona, and parda appear in the baptismal records. It seems that the infant death records were originally bound in a volume entitled, "Libro primero de p√°rvulos blancos difuntos..." In the twentieth century, these burial records were re-bound, combined with the baptismal records, and given the title, "Deaths Inf. White 1784-1826." The burials records range from 28 December 1784 to 3 August 1827, contain 413 entries, comprise pages 1-156.  All infant death entries include the date of death; date and place of burial; the infant's name and age at death; if known, parents' names, nationalities or places of previous residence, and military rank and/or administrative title (if applicable); and name and title of presiding priest. The baptismal records are from 1807, paginated as 1 and 2, and contain 5 entries.  All the baptismal records include the name of the individual; date of baptism; either date of birth or age at baptism; whether free or enslaved, and if enslaved, the owner's name; if known, parents' names; parents' nationalities or previous places of residence; whether parents are free or enslaved, and skin color; godparents' names, skin color, free or enslaved, and if enslaved, the owner's name.
